04281nam a22006855i 9781477304433DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211991txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773044337 a10.7560/7811532doi  a(DE-B1597)587137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a9781 aLamar, Howard R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTexas Crossings :bThe Lone Star State and the American Far West, 1836–1986 /cHoward R. Lamar. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (112 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- t1. Texas and the California Gold Rush -- t2. A Breed Apart: Texans i n the California Gold Rush, 1849- 1869 -- t3. Imperial Strategies: Texas, California, and the Southwest, 1836-1986 -- tNotes -- tSuggestions for Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Texas is not a place, it is a commotion!” exclaimed one early visitor to the state, underscoring the mobility and “get-ahead” spirit that have always characterized Texas and its people. In these thought-provoking essays, Howard R. Lamar looks specifically at the “crossings” that have characterized Texas history to see what effect these migrations to and through Texas have had on Texas, the Southwest, and links between Texas and California. Originally presented in 1986 at the University of Texas at Austin as the first George W. Littlefield Lectures in American History, these essays explore a previously neglected aspect of the western story: the influence of Texans—and other Southerners—on the character and history of the southwestern states. Lamar discusses the many efforts to establish overland trails, and later railroads, to California and how those efforts were fueled by the gold rush era of 1849–1850. He traces the influence of immigrant Texans and the flourishing southern community in California, particularly during the Civil War years. He follows the twentieth-century migration of “Okies,” whose desire to settle and resume their agricultural lifeways clashed with Californians’ preference for migrant workers. And he reveals how the discovery of oil, not only in Texas but also in California, western Canada, and Alaska, continues to link these regions. Texas has always been a place that people pass through, going either east-west or north-south. Texas Crossings explains what brought the people to Texas and what they carried away with them to California and the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCalifornia-Gold discoveries. 0aOverland journeys to the Pacific. 0aSouthwest, New-Description and travel. 0aTexas-Description and travel. 0aTrails-Southwest, New-History. 0aTrails-Texas-History. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGould, Lewis L.1 aGould, Lewis L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/78115340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477304433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477304433/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK